# ::snt A federal appeals court in Ohio later found, however, that the government had violated Warshak’s constitutional right to privacy.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.4
# ::snt The court said investigators should have convinced a judge that there was probable cause and obtained a search warrant, as though his messages had been stashed in a desk drawer.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.5
# ::snt Although the court let the conviction stand, the case highlighted the conflicting legal rules that govern electronic privacy.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.6
# ::snt Congress is now set to clarify those rules, bringing that quarter-century-old law, the Electronic Communications Privacy Act, or ECPA, in line with the Internet age.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.7
# ::snt On Thursday, the Senate Judiciary Committee will start deliberating a measure that would require the government to get a search warrant, issued by a judge, to gain access to personal emails and all other electronic content held by a third-party service provider.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.8
# ::snt The current statute requires a warrant for emails that are less than 6 months old, but it lets the authorities gain access to older communications – or bizarrely, emails that have already been opened – with just a subpoena and no judicial review.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.9
# ::snt The law governs the privacy of practically everything entrusted to the Internet – family photos stored with a Web service, journal entries kept online, company documents uploaded to the cloud, and the flurry of emails exchanged every day.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.10
# ::snt The problem is that it was written when the cloud was just a cumulus in the sky.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.11
# ::snt Silicon Valley companies as well as advocacy groups from the political left and right have been lobbying for change for many years, and reform legislation seems to be gaining broad political support.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.12
# ::snt Even the Justice Department appears to have approved one major change: requiring law enforcement to get a search warrant for all kinds of electronic content, no matter how long it has been in electronic storage or what exactly electronic storage means.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.13
# ::snt “Changing the law has become more of an imperative because of the growth of cloud computing, because everyone including members of Congress are storing sensitive info with third-party providers and they want it to be protected,” said Greg Nojeim, senior counsel at the Washington-based Center for Democracy and Technology, which is financed partly by Silicon Valley companies and which is part of a coalition pushing for reform.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.14
# ::snt “The technology is advancing and people realize the law has to keep pace.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.15
# ::snt Updating the bill could have a broader impact on civil cases as well, clarifying who can gain access to emails, photos and Facebook posts in corporate litigation and divorce court.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.16
# ::snt It could also lay out clearer rules for government agencies like the Internal Revenue Service to follow to gain access to private citizens’ emails.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.17
# ::snt The agency told Congress recently that it seeks search warrants before reading taxpayer emails, though its written policy says otherwise, according to an information request filed by the American Civil Liberties Union.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.18
# ::snt Courts across the country, apparently baffled by how to apply the existing law, which applies to content held in “electronic storage,” have ruled in sometimes contradictory ways over the privacy of electronic material in both civil and criminal cases.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.19
# ::snt In one prominent case, Lee Jennings sued a relative of his wife who broke into his Yahoo account and ferreted out emails describing an extramarital affair that were later used as incriminating evidence in divorce proceedings.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.20
# ::snt Jennings claimed a violation of his privacy under the electronic privacy act, but the highest court in his home state of South Carolina held that his emails, which sat on Yahoo’s servers, were not held in “electronic storage” and therefore were not covered by the statute.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.21
# ::snt A federal court in California years earlier had ruled differently in another case, interpreting “electronic storage” far more broadly.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.22
# ::snt Jennings’ lawyer, Neal K. Katyal, a former acting solicitor general in the Obama administration, asked the Supreme Court to reconcile the dueling interpretations.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.23
# ::snt The court declined to hear the case this month, effectively leaving it to Congress to clarify the law.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.24
# ::snt Although the appeals court ruling in the Warshak criminal case is binding only in the 6th Circuit, it has since become the default legal threshold for many Web companies.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.25
# ::snt Facebook says it turns over content created by users – pictures, posts, messages – only after it is served with a search warrant, though a subpoena suffices for basic subscriber information, including a user’s name and email address.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.26
# ::snt Twitter, too, says “requests for contents of communication require a U.S. search warrant,” and it informs users when it receives a request for information from a government agency.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.27
# ::snt Microsoft, which operates email and cloud storage services, follows a similar practice, insisting on a search warrant for “content,” including documents, photos, email and instant messages.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.28
# ::snt With a subpoena, the company can divulge a user’s Internet Protocol record, though, which can be used to establish a person’s location.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.29
# ::snt “The law is so old it doesn’t account for how we have turned into a digital society,” said Bryan Schilling, a lawyer at Microsoft.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.30
# ::snt He offered an offline analogy: “If somebody had a storage unit, law enforcement would be required to get a search warrant,” he said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.31
# ::snt “It’s the same thing now, as we store more and more of our content in the cloud, consumer or enterprise.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.32
# ::snt The original sponsor of the 1986 law, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., has called its overhaul his top priority for the year.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.33
# ::snt He and Sen. Mike Lee, R-Utah, have introduced a measure requiring law enforcement to obtain a warrant for all electronic content, including emails, regardless of how old they are.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.34
# ::snt That overhaul is backed by an unlikely coalition.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.35
# ::snt Amazon and Google, which offer cloud-based services to consumers and businesses, are lobbying for the change, along with startups like Evernote and Tumblr, which operate modern-day private diaries.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.36
# ::snt They have joined with advocacy groups as diverse as the American Civil Liberties Union and Americans for Tax Reform.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.37
# ::snt The issue of email privacy received the greatest attention last year, when Gen. David H. Petraeus, the former director of the Central Intelligence Agency, resigned after an inquiry into his email correspondence turned up evidence of an extramarital affair.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.38
# ::snt He and his biographer, Paula Broadwell, had exchanged amorous correspondence in a “draft” folder of a shared Gmail account, apparently to elude detection.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130424_0047.39
# ::snt Those draft messages, because they had not been transmitted across the Internet, could have been viewed by federal authorities with nothing more than a subpoena, according to current law.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.1
# ::snt GEORGE JONES IN REAL LIFE AND REAL TIME

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.2
# ::snt Early in 1977, a couple of years after he and Tammy Wynette had divorced, the country music star George Jones played a show at the Stardust Inn in Waldorf, Md., his first in the Washington area in several years.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.3
# ::snt I was then a young pop music critic at The Washington Post, so it fell to me to write a profile of the notoriously hard-drinking singer.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.4
# ::snt What followed was an experience so intense, so remarkable for its raw emotional force, that I could not help but think of it Friday, when it was announced that Jones had died in a Nashville, Tenn., hospital at the age of 81.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.5
# ::snt That weekend I learned two important things about Jones: that there was very little distance between him and his songs, and that the same qualities that made him a great artist also made his life a torment.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.6
# ::snt In those days he was still unashamedly carrying a torch for Wynette, who had left him because, as she put it in legal papers she filed, he “drinks to such an extent that he becomes completely and absolutely unmanageable.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.7
# ::snt On stage that weekend, he reworked songs like “She Thinks I Still Care” and “Picture Me Without You” so that they included references to her, making them almost embarrassingly personal, as if she were in the audience and he was singing only to her.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.8
# ::snt But it was on his tour bus between sets that I saw George Jones more achingly and nakedly vulnerable than any performer I have ever encountered, before or since that night.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.9
# ::snt He was dressed in a flashy leisure suit and wore a pair of glittering diamond rings on his left hand, including one with his initials, but as he talked about Wynette and how much he still loved her, he began to weep.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.10
# ::snt I don’t think he was drunk.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.11
# ::snt He talked about how he was trying to stay dry for Tammy, who by that time had already re-married and divorced again.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.12
# ::snt Within a year or two, he would develop a cocaine habit that would send his career off the rails, but there was no sign of that either.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.13
# ::snt This was just George Jones in real life and real time.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.14
# ::snt It is hard today, in a time when irony has become a dominant cultural mode and artists are screened from reporters by phalanxes of handlers, to imagine so public a breakdown happening or a celebrity letting his pain be so visible.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.15
# ::snt But Jones wasn’t ashamed or embarrassed by that display, and when he went back to the stage for a second set of what he described to me as “sad, sloppy tear-jerkers,” his singing was even more passionate and inspired, with his twangy, somewhat nasal voice cracking in all the right places with what had to be genuine feeling, not artifice.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.16
# ::snt Over a career that lasted nearly 60 years, Jones recorded more than 100 albums, and over and over again, he didn’t just sing the songs that were given to him.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.17
# ::snt In the best of his recordings, as on that night, he also inhabited them, so that anyone listening to him could be sure: He really means it, he has really lived this song about heartbreak or hangovers and knows what it means, poor soul.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.18
# ::snt As someone who grew up in Chicago listening mostly to the blues, I had no special fondness for country music, whose only local outlet in those days was the radio station WJJD.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.19
# ::snt But seeing George Jones live for the first time that cold night in southern Maryland was a revelation, because in his own highly idiosyncratic way he showed himself to be no less soulful a singer than Howlin’ Wolf on something like “How Many More Years” or Otis Redding on “I’ve Been Loving You Too Long.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.20
# ::snt Despite all the drinking and drug binges that would dog his career, Jones never lost that gift.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.21
# ::snt In 2009, assigned to write a profile of the Canadian singer-songwriter Leonard Cohen for this newspaper, I walked into Cohen’s New York hotel suite to find him playing one of Jones’ late-career gems, “Choices,” on his iPod.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.22
# ::snt Cohen expressed great admiration for Jones and then recited one of the song’s most powerful verses:

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.23
# ::snt I was tempted

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.24
# ::snt By an early age I found

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.25
# ::snt I liked drinkin’

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.26
# ::snt Oh, and I never turned it down

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.27
# ::snt There were loved ones

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.28
# ::snt But I turned them all away

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.29
# ::snt Now I’m living and dying

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.30
# ::snt With the choices I made

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.31
# ::snt @In part because of his consistent “nipping,” as he called it, Jones never enjoyed the crossover success of his contemporaries Johnny Cash and Merle Haggard, and so his passing will probably not have the broad cultural resonance that Cash’s did.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.32
# ::snt But he was, hands down, a superior singer, a fact obvious to everyone in the country music field: As Waylon Jennings once sang, “If we all could sound like we wanted to, we’d all sound like George Jones.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.33
# ::snt But even within the confines of “pure country,” whatever that term might mean today, Jones did not stand still.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.34
# ::snt He began his career very much in the mold of his idol Hank Williams, singing tunes about honky-tonks and carousing.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.35
# ::snt He never lost his affection for that genre, but over the years he also evolved into a master of ballad singing, especially on his duets with Melba Montgomery and Wynette, both before and after they were married.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.36
# ::snt And though a brief late ‘50s flirtation with rockabilly didn’t pan out, Jones also knew how to rock.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.37
# ::snt It’s almost forgotten now, but he and Elvis Presley once were co-headliners on a Louisiana Hayride tour, and generations of rock 'n’ roll bands, including ones I played in, have covered songs like “Why Baby Why,” “White Lightning” and “The Race Is On” and found them to be guaranteed crowd-pleasers.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.38
# ::snt Beginning in the 1980s, Jones, with the help of his fourth wife, Nancy Sepulvedo, pulled himself out of his tailspin.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.39
# ::snt But by then the country music mainstream had begun to move on to more polished styles, and Jones’ visceral approach fell out of fashion.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.40
# ::snt In recent years, Jones had thought of himself as a relic, and expressed bitterness at what he saw as the disregard for what he represented.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130426_0143.41
# ::snt All that may be true, but it can’t – and doesn’t – dim the magnificence of his achievements, any more than his personal weaknesses and demons did.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.1
# ::snt DEATH ROW INMATE ’ S REQUEST FOR DNA TESTING IS REJECTED

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.2
# ::snt The state of Mississippi rejected on Monday a request to submit physical evidence for DNA testing made by a prisoner scheduled to be put to death Tuesday evening.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.3
# ::snt Willie J. Manning, convicted in 1994 of murdering two college students, had been repeatedly rebuffed in the courts as he sought to have DNA tests performed on certain crime scene evidence.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.4
# ::snt But the most recent requests came about because of two letters sent by the Justice Department in recent days to the prosecutor who handled Manning’s trial.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.5
# ::snt The letters concerned the trial testimony of an FBI expert asked to examine “hair fragments” found at the scene of the murders.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.6
# ::snt The expert testified that in this case he could determine only that the hairs came from an African-American but that hair comparison analysis was capable, given better samples, of matching a hair to a particular individual.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.7
# ::snt Manning is black; the murder victims were white.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.8
# ::snt The prosecutor cited this testimony several times in his closing arguments.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.9
# ::snt In a letter dated May 2, the Justice Department said the expert’s testimony about the general capability of hair analysis – that it could match a hair to a specific individual – was erroneous and “exceeded the limits of the science.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.10
# ::snt Then, in a letter dated May 4, the department further said that such analysis could not “determine” that a hair came from a person of a certain race, as the expert testified at one point, only that the hair “possesses certain traits that are associated with a particular racial group.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.11
# ::snt The FBI offered in both letters to perform DNA testing on the hair fragments.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.12
# ::snt Manning’s lawyers argued that these letters constituted new evidence and thus that the hairs, as well as other evidence collected at the scene including a rape kit and fingernail scrapings, should be submitted for DNA testing before Manning is put to death.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.13
# ::snt In the response denying the requests, the state attorney general, Jim Hood, called the new requests a “red herring,” saying that the letters did not “represent new evidence,” nor did they repudiate the testimony given by the FBI expert in 1994.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.14
# ::snt Manning’s lawyers are still lobbying the governor for a stay of execution.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130506_0130.15
# ::snt On Friday, Manning’s brother and the Mississippi Innocence Project filed suit to preserve all the physical evidence for DNA testing even if the execution is carried out.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.1
# ::snt FOCUS TURNS TO THREE SUSPECTS IN BELGIAN DIAMOND ROBBERY

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.2
# ::snt PARIS – Investigators in three countries continued unraveling the plot behind a brazen $50 million diamond robbery in Belgium, focusing Thursday on a Swiss lawyer, a real estate businessman and a French luxury car exporter with a prison record for fraud.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.3
# ::snt After a series of raids Tuesday and Wednesday in Switzerland, Belgium and France, the authorities started releasing some of the more than 30 men who were arrested and questioned in connection with the Feb. 18 robbery, in which armed men in police suits attacked a Zurich-bound plane minutes before takeoff from the Brussels airport.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.4
# ::snt Investigators in Belgium and Switzerland suspect that a critical organizer in the plot was Marc Bertoldi, 43, a French car exporter whose listed address was in a wealthy seaside neighborhood of Antibes on the Cote d’Azur and who owns a restaurant in Casablanca, Morocco.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.5
# ::snt He was arrested Tuesday in France and remains in prison, awaiting a hearing May 16 in Metz for extradition to Belgium.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.6
# ::snt Investigators said Bertoldi’s arrival in Geneva after the theft had provided a critical breakthrough in the inquiry.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.7
# ::snt After Bertoldi’s arrest, the police trailed an unidentified Swiss lawyer and a real estate owner Wednesday as they made an exchange of a key to a cellar where some of the stolen diamonds were discovered.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.8
# ::snt Bertoldi’s lawyer, Olivier Rondu, said Thursday that his client denied the accusations against him and was willing to be extradited to Belgium to confront the charges.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.9
# ::snt “He has a surprising position that he wants to go to Belgium as quickly as possible to explain himself, because he says he has done nothing,” Rondu said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.10
# ::snt “He denies participating in the robbery at Brussels airport.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.11
# ::snt Rondu also confirmed that his client had been convicted in the past for fraud and robbery and had served a prison term.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.12
# ::snt In Switzerland, where eight people were arrested Wednesday, the real estate owner and the Swiss lawyer remained in detention.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130509_0160.13
# ::snt Francois Canonica, a lawyer for the Swiss lawyer, also denied any wrongdoing on his client’s part, telling a Swiss newspaper, Tribune de Geneve, “My client has faith that ultimately he will be acquitted.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.1
# ::snt MILITANT SAYS HE IS BEHIND FATAL NIGER ATTACK

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.2
# ::snt DAKAR, Senegal - Mokhtar Belmokhtar, the mastermind of the January seizure of an Algerian gas plant that left dozens of foreign hostages dead, has claimed responsibility for another terrorist attack - the suicide bombings on Thursday in Niger that killed about 30 people, including 24 soldiers and at least six jihadists.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.3
# ::snt If true, Belmokhtar’s claim would put one of the Sahel’s most hardened militants, whom Chad’s military said in March it had killed in battle, back at the center of the region’s fight against Islamist jihad.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.4
# ::snt Experts saw no reason to doubt Belmokhtar’s claim, despite the unconfirmed claim by the Chadian military, which said that Belmokhtar had died in the Ifoghas mountain range during the joint French-Chadian campaign against Islamist militants in northern Mali.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.5
# ::snt Neither France nor Algeria, where Belmokhtar has been a wanted man for years for his role in the 1990s civil war there, ever confirmed Chad’s assertion.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.6
# ::snt No proof was presented of his death, and a fellow militant later denied it in an Internet posting.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.7
# ::snt The latest claim by Belmokhtar - a veteran of training by al-Qaida in Afghanistan, years of terrorist acts against the Algerians and multiple kidnappings of Westerners in the Sahara - came hours after bomb-laden vehicles ripped through a military installation and a French-owned uranium mine in Niger.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.8
# ::snt Belmokhtar, who is considered perhaps the most redoubtable of the region’s surviving militants, also played a leading role in the Islamist takeover of northern Mali last year.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.9
# ::snt The new claim was made on a number of different websites.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.10
# ::snt In one, Belmokhtar himself, using his nom de guerre Khalid Abu al-Abbas, signed a claim on jihadist forums that fighters from his “Those Who Sign with Blood” brigade - the same group that carried out the Algeria attack - blew up the French mine and the Niger base, according to the SITE Monitoring Service, which tracks extremists.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.11
# ::snt The claim was posted by the same user who put out a video of Belmokhtar in December, SITE said, and it asserted that the attacks were in retaliation for purported assertions by Niger to have defeated the jihadists.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130525_0040.12
# ::snt “We warn all the countries that are intending to participate in the Crusader campaign on our land, even if in the name of peacekeeping, that we will make you taste the heat of death and wounds in your homelands and among your soldiers,” SITE quoted Belmokhtar as saying.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.1
# ::snt BRITAIN AND ECUADOR MAY DISCUSS ASSANGE CASE

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.2
# ::snt LONDON - The Ecuadorean foreign minister is due to travel to London this month and has offered to meet his British counterpart to discuss the impasse over the Julian Assange case, officials from both countries said on Monday.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.3
# ::snt Assange, the founder of the anti-secrecy group WikiLeaks, has been holed up for nearly a year in the tiny Ecuadorean Embassy here, stymying British attempts to extradite him to Sweden.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.4
# ::snt The Swedish authorities want to question Assange in connection with accusations that he sexually assaulted two women, but he has said he fears that the Swedes will in turn send him to the United States to answer questions about his role in helping disseminate classified government information via WikiLeaks.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.5
# ::snt The development concerning Assange came on the same day as the court-martial of Pfc. Bradley Manning, the Army private accused of passing on sensitive diplomatic and military information, was scheduled to begin in Maryland.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.6
# ::snt Manning has pleaded guilty to 20 of the 22 charges against him, but he has not admitted to the most serious charge, aiding the enemy.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.7
# ::snt Manning has said he gave the material to WikiLeaks, which then helped disseminate it.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.8
# ::snt Assange has never acknowledged that Manning was his source.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.9
# ::snt A spokesman for the Ecuadorean government said last week that the foreign minister, Ricardo Patino, planned to travel to London on June 16, three days before Assange’s first anniversary in the embassy, and to meet with Assange.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.10
# ::snt “The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Ecuador has informed U.K. authorities that Mr. Patino will be in London and has offered to meet with Foreign Secretary William Hague to discuss the case of Julian Assange,” the spokesman said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.11
# ::snt A spokesman for the British Foreign Office said it was informed of Patino’s trip on Friday and was “considering” his request for a meeting with Hague.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.12
# ::snt “U.K. government officials have been in regular contact with representatives of the Ecuadorean government, both in London and Quito, about Mr. Assange,” the Foreign Office said in a statement.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.13
# ::snt “We hope the visit will contribute to our joint commitment to finding a diplomatic solution to this issue.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130603_0111.14
# ::snt Last week, Reuters quoted Patino as saying his government was preparing a document in which it would argue that Britain is legally obliged to give Assange permission to travel to South America.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.1
# ::snt SOUTH AFRICAN LEADER CITES 'PROGRESS' IN MANDELA'S CONDITION

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.2
# ::snt JOHANNESBURG - After four days in the hospital battling a lung infection, former President Nelson Mandela of South Africa “is responding better to treatment,” President Jacob Zuma told Parliament in Cape Town on Wednesday.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.3
# ::snt “We are very happy with the progress that he’s now making, following a difficult few days,” Zuma said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.4
# ::snt It was the first report of an improvement in Mandela’s condition since he was admitted to a hospital in Pretoria early Saturday after suffering a recurrence of a persistent lung ailment, a legacy of the tuberculosis he contracted during the 27 years he was imprisoned for opposing apartheid.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.5
# ::snt His health has been frail lately, and this hospitalization was his fourth in the last seven months.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.6
# ::snt Government officials in the last few days had been more downbeat, describing Mandela’s condition as “serious but stable” with no improvement.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.7
# ::snt Mandela, 94, is being treated in an intensive care unit, where close family members have been visiting him regularly.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.8
# ::snt Among them are his daughters, his former wife Winnie Madikizela-Mandela and his grandson Mandla Mandela.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.9
# ::snt His current wife, Graça Machel, canceled a speech in London to be by his side.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.10
# ::snt Mandla Mandela, who is a traditional leader in the Eastern Cape village where his grandfather was born, spoke to reporters outside Mandela’s home.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.11
# ::snt “My grandfather is the father of the nation,” he said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.12
# ::snt “He’s embraced by the global community, and we appreciate the support that we’ve received.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.13
# ::snt As an underground leader of the banned African National Congress, Mandela was convicted of treason 49 years ago Wednesday.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.14
# ::snt He was sentenced to life in prison, but was released in 1990 as the government, under intense international pressure, began negotiating with Mandela and the ANC.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.15
# ::snt Mandela was elected as South Africa’s first black president in 1994 and served one term.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130613_0153.16
# ::snt He retired from public life in 2004, and has not been seen in public since 2010, when South Africa hosted the World Cup.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.1
# ::snt MILITANTS ATTACK U.N.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.2
# ::snt COMPOUND IN SOMALIA

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.3
# ::snt MOGADISHU, Somalia - Militants staged a deadly assault on a U.N. compound here Wednesday, the latest in a series of attacks that have chipped away at the security gains the Somali capital has experienced in recent years.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.4
# ::snt The Shabab, the fearsome Islamist militant group that once controlled much of the capital, claimed responsibility for the attack, which government officials said left at least 15 people dead, including seven attackers.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.5
# ::snt The assault began when Shabab militants blew up a pickup truck rigged with explosives outside the compound, witnesses said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.6
# ::snt Militants armed with rifles and wearing explosive vests then stormed the facility on foot.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.7
# ::snt Somali and African Union troops responded to the scene.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.8
# ::snt The ensuing firefight lasted more than an hour, punctuated by a series of blasts.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.9
# ::snt Somalia’s minister of interior and national security, Abdikarim Hussein Guled, told reporters that the dead included four foreigners, four Somalis working for the United Nations as security personnel, as well as the attackers.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.10
# ::snt In a statement, Somalia’s prime minister, Abdi Farah Shirdon Saaid, condemned “the senseless and despicable attack on innocent U.N. civilians.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.11
# ::snt Mogadishu has experienced a period of relative calm since African Union forces and the Somali army pushed back the Shabab, leading it to announce a hasty retreat from the city in 2011.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.12
# ::snt The militant group vowed to shift tactics more toward guerrilla assaults, assassinations and suicide bombings.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.13
# ::snt Militants “are now in complete control of the entire compound and the battle is still ongoing,” the Shabab said on its Twitter feed during the attack.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.14
# ::snt “Inside the compound are several clueless foreigners who were lulled into a false sense of security by a strong disinformation campaign!”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.15
# ::snt The Shabab, who have sworn allegiance to al-Qaida, said that the group’s Martyrdom Brigade had carried out the attack.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.16
# ::snt The U.N. compound sits on a busy stretch of road near the airport.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.17
# ::snt An ambulance worker, Abdirisak Moumin, said that he had collected 13 wounded civilians, six of whom died from their injuries.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.18
# ::snt Nicholas Kay, the U.N. special representative for Somalia, was outside the compound at a meeting nearby when the attack occurred.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.19
# ::snt He called the attack an act of terrorism intended to derail Somalia’s drive toward recovery after decades of war and instability.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.20
# ::snt While the United Nations would review its security procedures, “the U.N. is committed to its mission,” Kay said in a telephone interview.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130619_0092.21
# ::snt “We’re here to help and we’re here to stay.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.1
# ::snt VIGIL FOR MANDELA CONTINUES AS FAMILY MEMBERS HOLD EMERGENCY MEETING

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.2
# ::snt JOHANNESBURG - Singing crowds gathered outside the hospital where Nelson Mandela, South Africa’s former president, lay in a critical state for a third consecutive day Tuesday, as family members held an emergency meeting at his ancestral village.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.3
# ::snt Mandela’s eldest daughter, Makaziwe, at least two grandchildren and clan elders gathered at Mandela’s retirement house in Qunu, the remote southern village where he grew up, according to news media reports.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.4
# ::snt The subject of the meeting was not publicly disclosed, but Naplisi Mandela, an elder of the Mandela family, told the South African Press Association that they had gathered to discuss “delicate matters” - a euphemism widely interpreted to mean preparations for Mandela’s death.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.5
# ::snt Meanwhile, in Pretoria, doctors continued to treat Mandela for a lung ailment that he contracted on Robben Island, the notorious apartheid-era prison where he spent much of his 27 years behind bars until his release in 1990.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.6
# ::snt He was hospitalized June 8, his fourth hospitalization since late last year.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.7
# ::snt In a statement, President Jacob Zuma said Mandela’s condition was unchanged.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.8
# ::snt On Sunday, he visited Mandela and pronounced that his state had deteriorated from stable to critical.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.9
# ::snt Noting that Mandela’s 95th birthday is on July 18, Zuma urged South Africans to celebrate his achievements.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.10
# ::snt Still, after 18 days of anxious vigil, many appeared to be steeling themselves for the worst.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.11
# ::snt Larger-than-usual crowds gathered at the gates of the Mediclinic Heart Hospital to pay tribute to Mandela, as people dropped off cards at a growing shrine and sang songs.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.12
# ::snt “There is no one like you, Nelson Mandela,” one group sang in the Sotho language.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.13
# ::snt The emotional scenes were part of a perceptible shift in the national mood.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.14
# ::snt Until recently, many South Africans had avoided talking about Mandela’s fate, calling it culturally inappropriate to speculate about any ailing figure, much less one as revered as Mandela, who played a central role in South Africa’s transition from white-led minority rule to historic multirace elections in 1994.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.15
# ::snt But now many are openly talking about the prospect of bidding him farewell.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.16
# ::snt Mandela’s declining condition came as President Barack Obama prepared to arrive in South Africa on Friday on the second leg of an African tour that will also take him to Tanzania and Senegal.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130625_0044.17
# ::snt But the South African government said a planned meeting between Obama and Mandela - both the first black leaders of their countries - now looked unlikely.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.1
# ::snt AFGHAN COURT REVERSES CONVICTION IN TORTURE OF YOUNG WOMAN

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.2
# ::snt KABUL, Afghanistan - A court has reversed the convictions of three Afghans jailed for torturing a young relative who had refused to become a prostitute, alarming activists who had celebrated the guilty verdicts as a warning to all those who would seek to reverse the strides made by women here in the past 12 years.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.3
# ::snt A family had bought the young woman, Sahar Gul, from her stepbrother for $5,000 and had forced her to marry in 2011, when she was just 13 or 14.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.4
# ::snt When she refused to consummate the marriage, her in-laws locked her in a basement, where they burned her with hot wires, pulled out her fingernails and twisted her skin with pliers for months.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.5
# ::snt She was discovered in December 2011 curled up in a dank and dark corner of the cellar and badly malnourished.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.6
# ::snt Gul now lives in a shelter in Kabul.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.7
# ::snt Her case attracted widespread attention in Afghanistan and abroad.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.8
# ::snt Three of her in-laws were convicted last year of attempted murder, and each was sentenced to 10 years in prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.9
# ::snt The convictions were upheld on appeal, although her husband, who is in his 30s, remains at large.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.10
# ::snt Last month, however, in a decision that received little publicity, the Supreme Court sent the case back to the appeals court, saying that the violence appeared to warrant convictions for assault, not attempted murder, according to lawyers for the defendants.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.11
# ::snt The appeals court agreed, voiding the convictions and ordering that the defendants - Gul’s mother-in-law, sister-in-law and father-in-law - be set free.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.12
# ::snt The two women were released this week after about a year in prison, the lawyers said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.13
# ::snt They were not sure whether the father-in-law was yet out of prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.14
# ::snt As word spread in Kabul on Wednesday, Western officials said they were still gathering details but would probably have a response in the coming days.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.15
# ::snt Afghan women’s rights activists reacted with alarm and said they would press to have the three defendants retried.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.16
# ::snt “There’s smoke coming out of my hair.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.17
# ::snt I am so angry,” said Manizha Naderi, the executive director of Women for Afghan Women.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.18
# ::snt “This poor girl was in the basement for months.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.19
# ::snt If she wasn’t rescued, she would be dead.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.20
# ::snt She was starved and burned and had her fingernails pulled out.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.21
# ::snt How is this not attempted murder?”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130703_0214.22
# ::snt The courts’ decisions make “a statement that violence against women is not that important, that Afghanistan is becoming more conservative,” Naderi added.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.1
# ::snt MICHAEL MASTROMARINO, DENTIST GUILTY IN ORGAN SCHEME, DIES AT 49

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.2
# ::snt Michael Mastromarino, a former dental surgeon who became a tabloid sensation when he was charged with running a $4.6 million enterprise that plundered tissue and bone from corpses at funeral homes and sold them for transplants and research, died on Sunday at St. Luke’s Cornwall Hospital in Newburgh, N.Y. He was 49 and still serving a prison term.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.3
# ::snt The cause was complications of metastatic liver cancer, Mario Gallucci, Mastromarino’s lawyer, said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.4
# ::snt The technology that allows the transplantation of critical organs also enables the far more common transplantation of tissue: bone can be used to repair fractures, veins for heart bypass surgery, and tendons and ligaments can restore mobility.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.5
# ::snt Harvesting organs is allowed in New York state, provided the donor does not carry a potentially communicable disease, the survivors approve and the person is not too old.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.6
# ::snt But there are nowhere near enough willing donors to meet the demand for tissue, so the profit from one body can reach six figures.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.7
# ::snt Mastromarino became licensed by New York state to supply tissue banks and manufacturers of biological surgical instruments after his dental license was suspended in 2002 because of a drug addiction.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.8
# ::snt He established a network of undertakers, whom he paid up to $1,000 per corpse, and soon took on assistants and formed a business based in New Jersey, Biomedical Tissue Services.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.9
# ::snt He reportedly made $10,000 to $15,000 per body.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.10
# ::snt But Mastromarino harvested organs and tissue from bodies without consent from the survivors, the authorities said, and removed material from people with cancer, HIV and other diseases.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.11
# ::snt He then forged paperwork, including consent forms and death certificates, to make the cause of death and age acceptable.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.12
# ::snt The police began investigating irregularities at the Daniel George & Son Funeral Home in Bensonhurst, Brooklyn, in 2005.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.13
# ::snt News reports included lurid details, like what the police called a secret room in the funeral home equipped with specialized surgical equipment; leg bones replaced by PVC pipe so bodies would appear intact at viewings (this procedure is common in lawful bone removal); and the fact that one of the victims was Alistair Cooke, the British journalist and former host of “Masterpiece Theater,” whose arm and leg bones were taken even though he had had cancer.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.14
# ::snt Mastromarino was charged in 2006, along with two of his workers and an embalmer.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.15
# ::snt He pleaded guilty in 2008 to numerous charges of enterprise corruption, reckless endangerment and body stealing and was sentenced to 15 to 30 years in prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.16
# ::snt He and his wife, Barbara, agreed to pay $4.6 million to the district attorney’s office, to be distributed among the victims’ relatives.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.17
# ::snt Michael Mastromarino was born in Brooklyn on Sept. 16, 1963.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.18
# ::snt He graduated from the University of Pittsburgh and the New York University College of Dentistry.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.19
# ::snt Mastromarino had surgical offices in New Jersey and Manhattan.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.20
# ::snt He was a co-author, with Michael R. Wiland, of the book “Smile: How Dental Implants Can Transform Your Life.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.21
# ::snt Mastromarino, who was divorced, is survived by two sons, Michael and Jerry.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.22
# ::snt As for Cooke, his daughter, Susan Cooke Kittredge, said in an article in New York magazine that “he would have been just horrified” by the illegal harvesting.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130709_0087.23
# ::snt But, she said, “at the same time, he would have appreciated the Dickensian nature of it.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.1
# ::snt EXTRADITED COLOMBIAN TO FACE CHARGES OF DRUG TRAFFICKING

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.2
# ::snt A Colombian who has been described by his country’s president as “the last of the great kingpins” was extradited to the United States from Colombia on Tuesday to face charges that he manufactured large quantities of cocaine that he then trafficked to the U.S. and elsewhere.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.3
# ::snt Daniel Barrera is to be arraigned Wednesday and Thursday in U.S. district courts in Manhattan and Brooklyn, where he faces separate indictments.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.4
# ::snt After those prosecutions, he will be arraigned in Miami on additional charges, the authorities said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.5
# ::snt Barrera, also known as El Loco, was arrested in September in Venezuela as a result of a complex operation that included Colombian and Venezuelan authorities, the CIA, the Drug Enforcement Administration and the British intelligence.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.6
# ::snt He was later sent to Colombia, and his extradition was announced by the U.S. attorneys in the three jurisdictions and other officials, including Raymond W. Kelly, the police commissioner of New York; and Michele M. Leonhart, the head of the DEA.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.7
# ::snt An indictment in Manhattan says that Barrera relied on two Colombian terrorist organizations to carry out his operations, buying raw cocaine paste from members of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, and processing it in laboratories in areas controlled by another group, to which he paid fees.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.8
# ::snt Barrera’s organization produced upward of 400 tons of cocaine a year, “enriching itself and the two terrorist organizations it paid off,” said Preet Bharara, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.9
# ::snt Loretta E. Lynch, the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, said Barrera’s organization was “marked by its worldwide reach, ruthless criminality and staggering profits.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.10
# ::snt Barrera is charged in Manhattan with one count of narcotics importation conspiracy, which carries a maximum sentence of life in prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.11
# ::snt He faces a money laundering conspiracy charge in Brooklyn.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.12
# ::snt His lawyer declined to comment.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130710_0155.13
# ::snt Officials have said that Barrera, while residing in Venezuela, changed his appearance through plastic surgery, slept in different places and burned his fingertips to try to make it impossible to identify him.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.1
# ::snt EGYPT CALLS FOR NEW LOOK AT MORSI PRISON ESCAPE

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.2
# ::snt CAIRO - Egypt’s new rulers gave new credence to a court case against the ousted president, Mohammed Morsi, and members of the Muslim Brotherhood on Thursday over their escape from prison during the uprising that toppled his predecessor, Hosni Mubarak.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.3
# ::snt The case was transferred from an appeals court to the State Security prosecutor for further investigation.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.4
# ::snt No charges have been filed as yet.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.5
# ::snt Its acceptance by powerful prosecutors follows the arrest of many Muslim Brotherhood members and is a new blow to the group by the military-backed government.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.6
# ::snt The detentions have been criticized by rights groups and the Obama administration, which spent Thursday walking back remarks made early in the day by a State Department spokeswoman, Jen Psaki, seeming to criticize Morsi as undemocratic and in so doing seeming to validate the military’s move to oust him.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.7
# ::snt At her regular State Department briefing Thursday, asked about the reactions, Psaki said she had been “referring to all of the voices that have been - we have heard coming - the millions, I should say, coming from Egypt, and how strongly they have voiced their views about his rule.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.8
# ::snt But beyond that is up for the Egyptian people to determine.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.9
# ::snt The renewed investigation of Morsi and members of the Muslim Brotherhood dates to the uprising that led to the ouster of Mubarak in 2011.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.10
# ::snt Morsi and other Brotherhood leaders were arrested Jan. 28 and held in the Wadi Natroun prison north of Cairo, until they escaped two days later.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.11
# ::snt The case languished after Morsi was elected last year in the country’s first free presidential race, although local news outlets and Morsi’s opponents accused militants from Hamas, the Brotherhood’s Palestinian offshoot, of freeing their colleagues.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.12
# ::snt Morsi has not been seen publicly since his ouster July 3.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.13
# ::snt It is unclear where he is being held, or whether he and the others will face the charges in court.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.14
# ::snt The ouster of Morsi and the subsequent suppression of the Brotherhood has enraged the group’s members and led to a spate of scapegoating attacks by Muslim extremists against Christians they accuse of supporting his fall, rights activists said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130712_0047.15
# ::snt While tensions between the Christian minority and extremist elements in the Muslim majority are not new, attacks have been reported across the country - in the northern Sinai Peninsula, in a resort town on the Mediterranean Coast, in Port Said along the Suez Canal and in isolated villages in upper Egypt.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.1
# ::snt No special session, but protesters leave Capitol

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.2
# ::snt Times/Herald Tallahassee Bureau

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.3
# ::snt TALLAHASSEE — They weren’t able to persuade Gov. Rick Scott to call a special session on the controversial ''stand your ground’' law.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.4
# ::snt But the student activists known as the Dream Defenders drew national attention to their cause by holding the longest sit-in demonstration at the Florida Capitol in recent memory.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.5
# ::snt On Thursday, the Miami-based group announced that their record-setting protest is over — for now, at least.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.6
# ::snt ''After 31 days and 30 nights, we are leaving the Capitol for our next phase,'' Dream Defenders executive director Phillip Agnew said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.7
# ::snt Agnew said the group would register thousands of new voters in the coming months and return to the Capitol for legislative committee hearings in the fall.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.8
# ::snt The Dream Defenders’ occupation of the Capitol began July 16, three days after George Zimmerman was acquitted in the shooting death of Trayvon Martin, an unarmed teenager from Miami-Dade.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.9
# ::snt They promised to stay until Scott convened a special session on ''stand your ground’' and several other criminal justice issues.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.10
# ::snt ''We said if (Scott) would not give us a seat at the table, we would sleep on the floor until (he) gave us what we deserved,'' Agnew said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.11
# ::snt Scott met with the protesters July 18 but refused their demands.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.12
# ::snt The Dream Defenders tried to persuade state lawmakers to call the session themselves, but they couldn’t muster the 96 votes needed.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.13
# ::snt As of Thursday, 42 lawmakers had voted in favor of holding the session, 90 voted against, and 28 had yet to vote.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.14
# ::snt This week, House Speaker Will Weatherford called for the group’s departure.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.15
# ::snt The Dream Defenders claimed several victories, including a promise from Weatherford to hold a hearing on the ''stand your ground’' law this fall.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.16
# ::snt The group also secured meetings with the Florida Department of Law Enforcement to discuss racial profiling, Agnew said, and began a dialogue with the state Department of Juvenile Justice on the disproportionate number of young African-American men in prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.17
# ::snt Agnew said the Dream Defenders had not been pressured to wrap up their protest by the governor’s office or state law enforcement officials.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.18
# ::snt The Capitol Police who had watched over the group, Agnew added, ''deserved a raise.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.19
# ::snt The state spent a total of $153,630 on police overtime throughout the protest, according to FDLE.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.20
# ::snt The Dream Defenders didn’t anticipate their stay would last a month or that singer Harry Belafonte, rapper Talib Kweli or civil rights leaders Jesse Jackson and Julian Bond would join them in the Capitol.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.21
# ::snt ''Gov. Scott, through his inaction, created a new group of leaders who will have a lasting effect on Florida,'' said state Rep. Alan Williams, a Tallahassee Democrat who mentored the group.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.22
# ::snt When they packed up their belongings and left the Capitol Thursday evening, the young activists wondered aloud if there had been some level of divine intervention along the way.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.23
# ::snt On Wednesday, the state Department of Management Services announced plans to test the fire alarm system in the Capitol.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.24
# ::snt The testing would last from 8 p.m. until midnight, and involve an ''incredibly loud, high-pitch noise,'' according to a press release.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.25
# ::snt But before the testing began, the building adjacent to the Capitol was struck by lightning.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.26
# ::snt The Department of Management Services decided to perform maintenance on that building’s fire alarm system instead.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.27
# ::snt ''I don’t know how to explain it,'' Dream Defender Steven Pargett said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.28
# ::snt ''Some things are just meant to happen.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20130816_0151.29
# ::snt Times/Herald staff writers Tia Mitchell and Michael Van Sickler contributed to this report.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.1
# ::snt A PINK-SLIP THANKS FOR A MAJOR DECISION

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.2
# ::snt On Baseball);

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.3
# ::snt When John Gaherin, the chief labor negotiator for Major League Baseball, arrived for a meeting with the chief of the players union and baseball’s arbitrator, he carried an envelope in the pocket of his suit jacket.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.4
# ::snt It was two days before Christmas 1975, not a time to be conducting serious business, but Gaherin and Marvin Miller, the executive director of the union, knew why Peter Seitz, the arbitrator, had summoned them.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.5
# ::snt They knew that the subject of the meeting would be as serious a bit of business as baseball had ever experienced, and Gaherin went to the meeting prepared.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.6
# ::snt Seitz had informally telegraphed his decision in a grievance case, and now he would formally hand his written opinion to the two men.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.7
# ::snt As soon as he did, Gaherin handed Seitz the envelope.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.8
# ::snt “You’re fired,” it said in effect.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.9
# ::snt Such is the perilous life of impartial arbitrators in baseball and other professional sports.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.10
# ::snt Either side - the league or the union - has the right to fire them.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.11
# ::snt Like managers, they are hired to be fired.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.12
# ::snt “He told me he had expected as much,” Michael Seitz, Peter’s son, said in a recent telephone interview.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.13
# ::snt “His feeling was there was no other way to decide the case, because the baseball owners had been stupid in assuming that when they didn’t have a player under contract, they still had a contractual hold on him.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.14
# ::snt Fredric R. Horowitz, a 64-year-old lawyer from Santa Monica, Calif., is the latest to take a turn.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.15
# ::snt He will arbitrate Alex Rodriguez’s appeal of his 211-game suspension.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.16
# ::snt While arbitrators pay for their decisions, which anger either the owners or the players, they don’t always receive credit for the significance of their decisions.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.17
# ::snt Seitz, for example, was responsible for creating free agency in baseball with his decision in the 1975 Andy Messersmith-Dave McNally grievance, but I believe, as Marvin Miller used to complain, that some reports in the news media, including in The New York Times, mistakenly credited other cases: Curt Flood’s 1970 lawsuit against baseball and Catfish Hunter’s 1974 grievance against Charlie Finley.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.18
# ::snt Flood’s suit challenged the game’s reserve clause, the rule that bound a player to his team until he was traded, sold or released.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.19
# ::snt Hunter’s grievance contended that Finley, the Oakland Athletics’ owner, had breached his contract.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.20
# ::snt The Hunter case was exactly what the union argued, a breach-of-contract case.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.21
# ::snt Finley had not paid the premium on Hunter’s annuity, as stipulated in his contract, Richard Moss, the union lawyer, said, and the pitcher should be a free agent as a result.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.22
# ::snt Seitz, in his first year as baseball’s arbitrator, agreed with Moss’ argument and declared Hunter a free agent.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.23
# ::snt A year later, when Seitz ruled in the Messersmith-McNally grievance, he did not cite the Hunter decision as a basis for this decision.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.24
# ::snt As a breach-of-contract case, it affected no player but Hunter.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.25
# ::snt No other player could gain free agency based on Seitz’s decision on Hunter.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.26
# ::snt “It didn’t change the mind of a single owner,” Miller said of the Hunter decision in one of the many conversations we had on the subject.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.27
# ::snt "The owners’ position on free agency was the same after the Hunter case as it was before.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.28
# ::snt Nor, Miller added, did the Flood case affect the owners’ thinking on the reserve clause and free agency.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.29
# ::snt The reserve clause had forever been the tie that bound players to their teams, whether they liked it or not.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.30
# ::snt Flood did not like it, and when the St. Louis Cardinals traded him to Philadelphia, he opted to sue the commissioner rather than go to the Phillies, contending that he should have the right to play where he wanted.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.31
# ::snt The suit went all the way to the U.S. Supreme Court, where Flood lost.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.32
# ::snt The owners always argued that elimination of the reserve clause would ruin baseball, Miller said, and Flood’s loss in the lawsuit emboldened them to maintain their position.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.33
# ::snt As heroic as Flood was in pursuing his lawsuit, it fell well short of having an effect.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.34
# ::snt Its failure was one of the reasons the owners were so confident of winning the Messersmith-McNally grievance in court when they appealed Seitz’s decision, which said players could be free agents if they played the renewal year in their contract without signing a new contract.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.35
# ::snt What the owners failed to understand, in their inexperience in labor matters, was that judges rarely overruled an arbitrator’s decision, doing so only if an arbitrator’s authority had been exceeded.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.36
# ::snt The clubs and the commissioner have not done particularly well before arbitrators in instances where players have been suspended for conduct off the field.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.37
# ::snt That history continued last year when Shyam Das overturned Ryan Braun’s 50-game suspension.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.38
# ::snt Das was fired after his Braun ruling.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.39
# ::snt Baseball would have preferred settling all of the doping cases stemming from the investigation into Biogenesis, an anti-aging clinic that is believed to have distributed banned substances to baseball players.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.40
# ::snt The union also seemed eager to settle.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.41
# ::snt But Rodriguez has appealed his 211-game suspension.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130822_0136.42
# ::snt Given the volatility of the Rodriguez case, it would not be surprising if Horowitz’s first major case were his last.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.1
# ::snt FORMER JPMORGAN EMPLOYEE SURRENDERS IN 'LONDON WHALE' CASE

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.2
# ::snt Weeks after the U.S. government charged Javier Martin-Artajo, a former JPMorgan Chase employee, with hiding trading losses that ultimately reached more than $6 billion, he had his first day in court Tuesday as he surrendered to Spanish authorities and kicked off what could be a lengthy extradition process.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.3
# ::snt Martin-Artajo, a Spaniard who worked in the bank’s London office, was released soon after his surrender and arrest.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.4
# ::snt He agreed to remain at the disposal of the Spanish judiciary, but it was unclear whether his passport was confiscated to prevent him from leaving the country, according to a person briefed on the matter.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.5
# ::snt The criminal charges stem from a risky bet at JPMorgan’s chief investment office in London, where Martin-Artajo worked.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.6
# ::snt The bet involved so-called credit derivatives, which allow traders to bet on the perceived health of companies like American Airlines.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.7
# ::snt When the bet soured in the spring of 2012, prosecutors claim, Martin-Artajo and Julien Grout, a lower-ranking employee, deliberately overstated the value of their positions to hide hundreds of millions of dollars in losses.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.8
# ::snt The two were charged with wire fraud, falsifying bank records and contributing to false regulatory filings.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.9
# ::snt Prosecutors also charged them with conspiracy to commit those crimes.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.10
# ::snt The arrest in Spain, the latest development in an episode that left a rare stain on JPMorgan’s once-stellar reputation, underscores the challenge U.S. authorities face in their pursuit of the traders.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.11
# ::snt After announcing charges this month against Martin-Artajo and Grout, federal prosecutors and the FBI in Manhattan have encountered logistical hurdles.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.12
# ::snt British police issued an arrest warrant for Martin-Artajo at the behest of authorities in New York, and then visited his house in London only to find that he was gone.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.13
# ::snt According to his lawyers, Martin-Artajo left London “on a long-planned vacation” to his native Spain without knowing of the pending charges.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.14
# ::snt Grout, for his part, left London this year for his native France, which typically does not extradite its citizens.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.15
# ::snt His lawyer, Edward Little, explained that his client also spent a brief period in the U.S., where his wife’s family lives.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.16
# ::snt According to a person close to the case, both of the former traders have indicated through their lawyers that they are open to extradition but only if prosecutors recommend bail.

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.17
# ::snt Prosecutors have not charged a third trader, nicknamed “the London Whale.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20130828_0147.18
# ::snt That trader, Bruno Iksil, has reached a deal with the authorities in Manhattan that will spare him charges as long as he cooperates against his two former colleagues.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.1
# ::snt LEADER OF FAR-RIGHT PARTY IN GREECE IS JAILED

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.2
# ::snt ATHENS, Greece - The leader of the extreme-right Golden Dawn party was returned to custody Thursday after appearing before a Greek magistrate on charges of setting up a criminal organization, part of the government’s crackdown on a party described by Greek and European authorities as neo-Nazi and violent.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.3
# ::snt The magistrate’s order to remand Nikos Michaloliakos, the first political party leader to face jail since Greece’s seven-year military dictatorship ended in 1974, came a day after three of his fellow lawmakers facing similar charges were released from custody and told not to leave the country, and a fourth was ordered held pending trial.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.4
# ::snt During more than six hours of testimony in an Athens courtroom, Michaloliakos condemned the murder last month of a 34-year-old hip-hop artist and anti-fascist, Pavlos Fyssas, by a self-professed supporter of Golden Dawn, and said he did not know whether members of the party were involved in violence, according to a court official.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.5
# ::snt “I condemn the murder, like I condemn violence in general,” he was quoted as saying.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.6
# ::snt “I am not a Nazi.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.7
# ::snt Leaving court early Thursday, Michaloliakos was defiant.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.8
# ::snt “Long live Golden Dawn!

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.9
# ::snt Victory!” he declared as his wife, Eleni Zaroulia, another Golden Dawn member of Parliament, cried, “You’re a diamond!” and his daughter, Ourania Michaloliakou, urged him, “Don’t buckle, don’t give in!”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.10
# ::snt Michaloliakos was transferred to the capital’s high-security Korydallos prison later in the day along with Yiannis Lagos, another Golden Dawn lawmaker.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.11
# ::snt Giorgos Patelis, the head of the party’s chapter in Nikaia, near the spot where Fyssas was fatally stabbed, and an officer from the regional police precinct accused of supplying Golden Dawn with information were taken to two other jails in central Greece, state television reported.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.12
# ::snt According to the police, Lagos telephoned Michaloliakos half an hour after the killing of Fyssas on Sept. 18.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.13
# ::snt The lawmaker has been tied to protection and prostitution rackets as well as blackmail and money laundering, according to secret service documents leaked to the Greek media this week.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.14
# ::snt Later Thursday, a sixth lawmaker, Christos Pappas, the party’s second in command, was also ordered returned to custody after testifying for at least six hours before a magistrate.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.15
# ::snt He was to stay overnight at the Athens police headquarters before his transfer to prison.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131003_0269.16
# ::snt Arriving at the capital’s court complex, Pappas told reporters, “Golden Dawn will run in the next elections, whenever they may be.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.1
# ::snt PROTESTS AS CITY COLLEGE CLOSES A STUDENT CENTER

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.2
# ::snt Julie Turkewitz contributed reporting.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.3
# ::snt NEW YORK - It was just a small room, one of hundreds in City College’s North Academic Center, but over the years the Guillermo Morales/Assata Shakur Student and Community Center had taken on a significance beyond its square footage.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.4
# ::snt To student organizers who used it as their meeting space, it was a place for lesbian and gay activists, women’s rights groups, community organizations and others to make common cause.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.5
# ::snt To outside critics it was a symbol of campus politics gone berserk, its unofficial name a glorification of City College alumni who had joined revolutionary organizations and gone on the lam.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.6
# ::snt But officials at City College, part of the City University of New York, insisted that charged history was not a factor when they decided that the room would be better used as an annex for the school’s career services office, two floors below.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.7
# ::snt Without notice, security officers entered the room this past weekend, boxed up and removed its contents - and just to be on the safe side, locked down the entire building, including the library.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.8
# ::snt With just a day to go before midterm exams, the library was reopened after a few hours.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.9
# ::snt But Room 3/201 was not, resulting at least for a brief while in the incongruous sight of closed doors emblazoned with a bold, black fist, below a crisp white sign that read Careers and Professional Development.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.10
# ::snt (The door had been repainted, without the fist, as of Monday afternoon.)

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.11
# ::snt Given the center’s history, it could not have come entirely as a surprise when its former occupants let their dissatisfaction be known.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.12
# ::snt They organized protest rallies, distributed fliers, posted videos and demanded that City College be shut down.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.13
# ::snt A protester was arrested.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.14
# ::snt And just in time for an outdoor demonstration on Monday, someone set off a fire alarm, sending hundreds of people out onto the plaza.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.15
# ::snt “I think that the CUNY administration is really scared of a lot of the organizing and community-building coming out of the building,” said Alyssia Osorio, director of the Morales/Shakur Center.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.16
# ::snt “We provide so many services for the community - know-your-rights training, a farm share that provides healthy food, we’ve run a soup kitchen, we have provided baby-sitting services for people in the community.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.17
# ::snt Deidra Hill, vice president of communications at City College, called the administration’s takeover of the room a matter of space.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.18
# ::snt She said the career services office needed a quiet area where students can “meet with outside employers, with alumni, to seek advice on careers.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.19
# ::snt City College said the unusually swift action was necessary.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.20
# ::snt “We were concerned that we might have to move people, and that would not have been safe,” Hill said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.21
# ::snt As for the protests, “Students were exercising their free speech rights, which the college supports,” she said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.22
# ::snt The City College students whom the center’s name honors have never visited.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.23
# ::snt Guillermo Morales, a leader of the FALN, a Puerto Rican independence group that claimed responsibility for a deadly bombing in New York, fled to Cuba.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.24
# ::snt So did Shakur, who as a member of the Black Liberation Army was convicted in the 1973 killing of a New Jersey State trooper.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.25
# ::snt In 2006, a student objected to the name of the center.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.26
# ::snt In the ensuing controversy, CUNY’s chancellor ordered that it be changed.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.27
# ::snt But it stuck.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.28
# ::snt Taf Sourov, 19, a member of the Revolutionary Student Coordinating Committee, a group that regularly met there, said he believed the closing was retaliation for student protests against David H. Petraeus, the former CIA director and military commander, who is teaching a course at the Macaulay Honors College.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.29
# ::snt “I practically lived out of the room,” Sourov said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.30
# ::snt “I would do my homework in there.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.31
# ::snt I did my political work in there.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.32
# ::snt I would socialize in there.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131022_0102.33
# ::snt I feel like part of me is ripped out.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.1
# ::snt Dewhurst wants to bill feds for undocumented prisoners

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.2
# ::snt AUSTIN, Texas -- Days after calling for the impeachment of President Barack Obama, Lt. Gov. David Dewhurst is demanding that the president pay for the 130,000 undocumented immigrants who are housed in county jails across Texas -- a tab that could run nearly $157 million in the past two years alone.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.3
# ::snt In a letter to Obama, Dewhurst said the federal government should reimburse Texas counties for the cost of housing the undocumented immigrants because the feds have failed to secure the U.S. Mexico border as they should have.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.4
# ::snt ''It’s time we ask for that money back,'' Dewhurst said in an email to supporters this week, asking them to sign a petition supporting his position.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.5
# ::snt ''It’s outrageous that county jails pay for housing to more than 130,000 people that illegally enter our state.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.6
# ::snt ''In my experience, I believe the immigration conversation begins and ends with strict border security, as our counties can no longer fund this massive financial burden.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.7
# ::snt In his letter to Obama, Dewhurst wrote: ''The dollars expended in this fashion would be better spent enhancing law enforcement efforts to better protect our citizens.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.8
# ::snt No word yet from Washington on what they think of Dewhurst’s demand, but don’t expect a check to be arriving anytime soon.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.9
# ::snt Dewhurst, who has drawn three GOP challengers in his re-election bid, has made a sharp turn to the right in his political rhetoric since losing a U.S. Senate runoff to tea party star Ted Cruz in July 2012.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.10
# ::snt Two weeks ago, Dewhurst publicly advocated Obama’s impeachment at a tea party forum in Fort Worth -- a move that drew surprise since it came from Texas’ No. 2 officeholder.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.11
# ::snt State and county officials have complained for years that detained immigrants are costing local taxpayers, and federal officials have declined to reimburse any costs because the jailed suspects are being held on local charges.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.12
# ::snt Similarly, state officials have also complained that state prisons are holding thousands of undocumented immigrants who were convicted of state crimes.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.13
# ::snt At one point last year, well over 12,000 state convicts had deportation detainers on them -- meaning that as soon as they complete their sentence or are paroled they are subject to being deported, officials said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.14
# ::snt Most are Mexican citizens, prison officials said.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.15
# ::snt Proposals to deport convicts serving time for nonviolent crimes before they were paroled have failed to gain support from legislative leaders, who feared if they were paroled and returned home they would simply slip back across the border into Texas.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.16
# ::snt The savings from that plan were estimated to be at least $15 million, officials said at the time.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.17
# ::snt Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0042.18
