# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.1
# ::snt IKE SKELTON, FORMER CONGRESSMAN FROM MISSOURI, DIES AT 81

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.2
# ::snt Ike Skelton, a Democratic congressman who was ousted in the Republican sweep of 2010 after serving his Missouri district for more than 30 years, died Monday in Arlington, Va.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.3
# ::snt He was 81.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.4
# ::snt His death was confirmed by the law firm Husch Blackwell, where Skelton was a partner.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.5
# ::snt He died at Virginia Hospital Center after a brief illness, according to a statement from his family.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.6
# ::snt Skelton, who was first elected to the House in 1976, was known as an expert on national defense and served as the chairman of House Armed Services Committee from 2007 until leaving office.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.7
# ::snt He was re-elected time and time again in a deeply conservative district that stretches from the Kansas City suburbs to the Ozarks, and he had a long record of supporting two local military institutions: Fort Leonard Wood and Whiteman Air Force Base, which he secured as the base for the nation’s fleet of B-2 bombers.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.8
# ::snt “He led an exemplary life of honor, courage and public service,” Maurice Watson, the chairman of Husch Blackwell, said Monday in a statement.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.9
# ::snt “His commitment to our country, the state of Missouri and the men and women who serve our nation in the armed services was unsurpassed.”

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.10
# ::snt Skelton was a social conservative who supported gun rights, opposed abortion rights and voted against President Barack Obama’s health care law.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.11
# ::snt Before his defeat, he had not received less than 60 percent of the vote since 1982.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.12
# ::snt But that record was not enough to overcome the national tide of Republicans elected to the House in 2010.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.13
# ::snt Rep. Vicky Hartzler, the Republican who beat Skelton and still holds the seat, received support from many Tea Party members and tied him to Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., then the House speaker.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.14
# ::snt Skelton was born in Lexington, Mo., and won his first election in 1956 to become the prosecuting attorney in Lafayette County.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.15
# ::snt He served in the Missouri state Senate before entering Congress.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.16
# ::snt After leaving the House, he became a partner at Husch Blackwell, working in its Missouri and Washington offices.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0091.17
# ::snt He is survived by his wife, Patricia Martin, and three sons.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.1
# ::snt Scott rejects Bar's lists

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.2
# ::snt Times/Herald Tallahassee Bureau

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.3
# ::snt TALLAHASSEE — Gov. Rick Scott, seeking to bring the court system more in line with his conservative outlook, has repeatedly rejected lists recommended to him by the Florida Bar of lawyers seeking to screen candidates for judgeships.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.4
# ::snt Scott has rejected dozens of attorneys the Bar has nominated to serve on judicial nominating commissions, created decades ago to professionalize the bench and make merit and qualifications at least as important as political connections.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.5
# ::snt ''He wants people with humility,'' says Scott’s chief counsel, Pete Antonacci, ''and he wants judges who will follow the law and not make it up as they go along.''

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.6
# ::snt The Bar said Scott’s two predecessors, Charlie Crist and Jeb Bush, never rejected any of its nominees.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.7
# ::snt All 26 nominating commissions for the trial and appellate courts and the Supreme Court are composed of nine members.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.8
# ::snt Scott appoints five members of his choosing and must appoint four others from lists provided by the Bar’s Board of Governors, some of whom are liberal Democrats who did not support Scott’s election.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.9
# ::snt The governor has rejected the lists 16 times and has never publicly given a reason and is not required to do so.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.10
# ::snt Scott has sent back so many Bar-recommended names that the group keeps a five-page spreadsheet to track them.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.11
# ::snt Lawyers who are registered Democrats, are aligned with left-leaning groups or who promote themselves as trial lawyers appear to have little hope of gaining the governor’s favor.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.12
# ::snt Scott’s list of rejections includes:

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.13
# ::snt * Benjamin Crump of Tallahassee, a criminal defense lawyer honored by the NAACP for his legal advocacy and who is best known for his firm’s representation of the family of Trayvon Martin.

# ::id nyt_eng_20131029_0228.14
