# ::snt Mine Workers and Supporters to Encircle Peabody HQ in Downtown St. Louis

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.7
# ::snt Union says retirees and dependents must receive health care benefits earned during decades of labor in company mines

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.8
# ::snt St. Louis – Thousands of mine workers and supporters plan to march around the headquarters of Peabody Energy in St. Louis this coming Tuesday, Sept. 24th.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.9
# ::snt The event is the latest in a series of protests directed at the world’s largest private-sector coal company, which reported $90 million in net income in the second quarter of 2013.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.10
# ::snt Peabody executives, however, are so far refusing to honor the company’s obligation to provide critically needed health care benefits for retired miners.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.11
# ::snt Who: Mine workers and supporters, including:

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.12
# ::snt · Cecil Roberts, International President, UMWA

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.13
# ::snt · Hugh McVey, President, Missouri AFL-CIO

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.14
# ::snt · Terrence Melvin, President, Coalition of Black Trade Unionists

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.15
# ::snt · Claude Cummings, Vice President, CWA District 6

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.16
# ::snt · Rev. Jonathan Stratton, Episcopal Diocese of Missouri

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.17
# ::snt What: March encircling Peabody Headquarters, calling for the company to honor its obligations to retired miners and their dependents.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.18
# ::snt When: Tuesday, September 24th, 10 am (Central Time)

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.19
# ::snt Where: March to begin at Crowne Plaza Hotel, 200 N. Fourth Street.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.20
# ::snt Marchers will proceed on Pine St. to Broadway, to Market.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.21
# ::snt Then on Market Street to circle around Peabody headquarters along Market, Eighth, Chestnut and Seventh Streets.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.22
# ::snt Marchers will then proceed to Kiener Plaza for a rally.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.23
# ::snt “The Patriot Coal chapter of this fight is behind us, now it’s time for Peabody Energy and Arch Coal to meet their responsibilities,” said UMWA President Roberts.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.24
# ::snt Last month, UWMA members approved a settlement with Patriot Coal, a company created by Peabody in 2007, which among other provisions established a mechanism for payment of health care benefits for retired miners.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.25
# ::snt However, long-term funding for those benefits has not been secured.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.26
# ::snt The union also won a court ruling in August establishing Peabody’s continued obligations to 3,100 miners and dependents, whose benefits remained with Peabody at the time of the Patriot spinoff.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.27
# ::snt Arch Coal, another profitable company, dumped its retiree obligations into a company called Magnum Coal in 2005.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.28
# ::snt Magnum was subsequently acquired by Patriot, which entered bankruptcy reorganization last year.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.29
# ::snt “This fight is anything but over,” said Roberts.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.30
# ::snt “Executives of these companies have to understand that miners and their families know the real story of what happened here – and because of our efforts, so do millions of working people across the country.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.31
# ::snt Men and women worked underground for decades to earn these benefits.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.32
# ::snt These companies are profitable, and they must step up to meet their obligations to these retirees.”

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.33
# ::snt The union’s ongoing effort to win full benefits for all affected retired miners includes a lawsuit against Peabody and Arch, filed in West Virginia; legislation in Congress to aid retired miners and their dependents, sponsored by both Republicans and Democrats; and an ongoing public education, advertising and community action campaign.

# ::id web1-eng-DF-183-195729-5441907_0001.34
# ::snt Additional information is available at FairnessAtPatriot.org.

